Req. No. 3769 Page 4

1 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1330.2 of Title 74, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. Any pharmacy benefits manager (PBM) contract with a state
5 plan shall:
6 1. Declare state plan ownership of all plan-specific
7 operational data including, but not limited to, claims, pricing,
8 rebates, formulary, utilization management outputs, audit data, and
9 any such related reporting maintained by the PBM or any affiliate or
10 subcontractor of such PBM;
11 2. Provide that the state plan have broad audit rights and
12 shall determine designated auditors over any PBM and any affiliates
13 or subcontractors of such PBM to verify compliance with contract
14 provisions;
15 3. Establish network adequacy including rural access and
16 compliance with any applicable pharmacy choice and access rules
17 established by contract;
18 4. Provide that the state plan have exclusive authority over
19 formulary selection, tiering, preferred status, exclusions,
20 specialty designation, and utilization management of any provisions
21 of such contract. Nothing in this paragraph shall be construed to
22 prohibit the PBM from providing recommendations to the state plan
23 for formulary selection, tiering, preferred status, exclusions,
24 specialty designation, or utilization management; and
Req. No. 3769 Page 5

1 5. Offer for inclusion in such contract, at the election of the
2 state plan, one or more set pricing guarantee methodologies for
3 covered outpatient drugs including, but not limited to, National
4 Average Drug Acquisition Cost (NADAC) plus a dispensing fee, maximum
5 allowable cost (MAC) pricing, or any objectively verifiable
6 benchmark approved by the state plan.
7 B. No PBM shall:
8 1. Modify criteria, add restrictions, or change placement of
9 drugs on a formulary without written authorization by the state plan
10 to make such changes;
11 2. Restrict or prohibit the state plan from requiring or
12 negotiating set pricing guarantees;
13 3. Include any plan design or incentive to steer any members of
14 the state plan to a pharmacy affiliated with such PBM unless such
15 plan design or incentive is authorized in writing by the state plan
16 after submission of an impact analysis established pursuant to
17 subsection A of Section 3 of this act;
18 4. Establish network terms or reimbursement methodologies that
19 are less favorable to nonaffiliated pharmacies than to affiliated
20 pharmacies;
21 5. Establish gag clauses limiting the state plan’s ability to
22 share contract terms, performance metrics, audit results, or cost
23 data with oversight entities, auditors, actuaries, or counsel. Any
24
Req. No. 3769 Page 6

1 cont ract terms shared pursuant to this paragraph shall be subject to
2 reasonable confidentiality; and
3 6. Establish contract provisions that create reimbursement or
4 network conditions that exclude specific pharmacies from the network
5 without documented and state plan-approved access and cost
6 justifications.
7 C. The PBM shall be required to disclose any affiliates or
8 subcontractors of such PBM to the state plan prior to the awarding
9 of a contract and shall disclose any additional affiliate or
10 subcontractor at no fewer than thirty (30) days after such affiliate
11 or subcontractor is associated with the PBM.
12 D. All rebates and formulary rebates including, but not limited
13 to, administrative or data fees or network or service fees shall be
14 passed through to the state plan. Nothing in this subsection shall
15 be construed to require the pass-through of any amounts authorized
16 as fixed and separately stated administrative fees to the state
17 plan.
18 E. Any guarantees established by the contract between a PBM and
19 a state plan shall be determined by total net cost and access
20 outcomes and shall not be determined by rebate volume. Such
21 performance guarantees shall include clear remedies in the form of
22 credits payable by the plan for failure to comply with the
23 provisions of the contract.
24 F. A PBM shall:
Req. No. 3769 Page 7

1 1. Maintain System and Organization Controls (SOC) Type 2
2 certification for the duration of the contract with the state plan;
3 and
4 2. Provide to the state plan, all plan-specific operational
5 data and reporting in the form and medium prescribed by the plan
6 within the time frame established by the contract, or if not
7 specified, within five (5) business days of the state plan’s request
8 for then existing data, and within thirty (30) days after the close
9 of each month for monthly files and reports. Such PBM shall not
10 withhold or delay such data or charge any amount except for the
11 fixed administrative fee for extraction, access, interfaces,
12 licensing, or delivery, including any fees imposed by affiliates or
13 subcontractors of such PBM, and shall remain responsible for
14 compliance even if such data is held or processed by such affiliate
15 or subcontractor.
16 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
17 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1330.3 of Title 74, unless there
18 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
19 A. The pharmacy benefits manager (PBM) shall provide a written
20 impact analysis to the state plan prior to the state plan approving
21 any change to contract provisions, formularies, utilization
22 management criteria, network design, reimbursement methodologies, or
23 any plan design or incentive pursuant to paragraph 3 of subsection B
24 of Section 2 of this act. No change shall be implemented unless the
Req. No. 3769 Page 8

1 stat e plan authorizes in writing such change. Such impact analysis
2 shall include at minimum:
3 1. The total number of members impacted by each proposed
4 change;
5 2. The total net plan cost impact of each proposed change;
6 3. The member out-of-pocket impact of each proposed change;
7 4. The state plan cost impact of each proposed change; and
8 5. The pharmacy access impact of each proposed change,
9 including rural access impacts.
10 B. The PBM shall submit an electronic report in a form and
11 medium prescribed by the state plan that shall include for each
12 prescription drug claim itemized, claim-level reporting data
13 sufficient to validate the following:
14 1. The date of dispensing;
15 2. The National Drug Code (NDC);
16 3. The drug quantity;
17 4. The number of days’ supply;
18 5. The dispensing pharmacy identifier in the form of the
19 National Provider Identifier (NPI) and the National Council for
20 Prescription Drug Programs (NCPDP) Number;
21 6. If the dispensing pharmacy is affiliated with the PBM;
22 7. The final total payment received by the dispensing pharmacy
23 from all sources;
24 8. The ingredient cost paid to the dispensing pharmacy;
Req. No. 3769 Page 9

1 9. The final dispensing fee paid to the dispensing pharmacy;
2 10. Any post-adjudication fees, withholds, recoupments,
3 incentives, or other adjustments applied to the claim;
4 11. The total gross amount billed to the state plan for the
5 claim;
6 12. The total gross amount billed to the state plan for the
7 drug’s ingredient cost;
8 13. The total gross amount billed to the state plan for the
9 dispensing fee;
10 14. The total net amount billed to the state plan for the
11 claim;
12 15. The total net amount billed to the state plan for the
13 drug’s ingredient cost;
14 16. The total net amount billed to the state plan for the
15 dispensing fee; and
16 17. All other amounts charged in connection with the claim.
17 C. Any contract term in violation of the provisions of this act
18 shall be voidable and severable at the election of the state plan.
19 Any violation of the provisions of this act may constitute a
20 material breach and may be grounds for termination for cause, in
21 addition to any other remedies available under contract or law.
22 D. Any request for proposal for PBM services for the state plan
23 shall include:
24 1. Bidder certification of compliance;
Req. No. 3769 Page 10

1 2. A compliance narrative; and
2 3. Sample contract language demonstrating compliance with the
3 provisions of this act.
4 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1330.4 of Title 74, unless there
6 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 In evaluating proposals for a contract between a pharmacy
8 benefits manager (PBM) and the state plan, the state plan may assign
9 favorable scoring or weighting to proposals based on factors in
10 addition to price including, but not limited to:
11 1. Accessibility and in-state presence, including the ability
12 of the PBM to provide regular in-person meetings with state
13 officials and the positive economic impact of the PBM’s operations
14 within this state, including employment, investment, and other
15 economic activity within this state;
16 2. Compliance history, including the PBM’s record of regulatory
17 actions, legal judgments, settlements, or enforcement actions
18 involving a state, self-insured plan, or governmental entity
19 relating to pharmacy reimbursement, claims processing, audit
20 practices, or other PBM business activities; and
21 3. Transparent pricing models, including the offering of a
22 flat-fee-per-claim-processed model or a per-member-per-month
23 administrative fee model that minimizes or eliminates spread pricing
24 and other undisclosed revenue streams.
Req. No. 3769 Page 11

1 SECTION 5. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
